\b\fs36 \cf2 COVID-19 disrupts the Earth System\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\sa240\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs24 \cf2 Under usual daily life, the human footprint on the Earth System is vast. As a result, a very large perturbation is required to cause an observable difference from this \'91business-as-usual\'92 baseline: COVID-19 is providing that perturbation. As of July 2020, as much as half the world\'92s population has been under some version of sheltering orders{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR7"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 7}} (Fig.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Fig2"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2a}}). These orders have substantially reduced human mobility and economic activity (Fig.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Fig2"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2b}}), with ~70% of the global workforce living in countries that have required closures for all non-essential workplaces and ~90% living in countries with at least some required workplace closures{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR8"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 8}}.\
The scale of this socioeconomic disruption is likely to be detected in the Earth System at local to global scales (Fig.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Fig1"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 1}}). Some responses are direct, while others will result from interactions between humans, ecosystems and climate. The impacts of the socioeconomic disruption are, thus, also likely to vary across timescales: although the direct impacts of the reduction in human mobility will be strongest during the sheltering period, many of the most lasting impacts could result from cascading effects initiated by the economic recession, some of which (such as those induced by changes in public policy, the structure of the economy and/or human behaviour) could persist for decades following the initial economic recovery.\
The reduction of human activities, and the efforts to manage their revival, have varied around the world (Fig.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Fig2"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2}}). Given the variations in the timing, strength and approach to sheltering{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR7"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 7}}, it may be possible to track effects through the components of the Earth System. Likewise, because the large-scale reduction in human activity will necessarily be temporary, it will be possible to observe whether or how Earth System processes return to their previous states after activity returns to something approaching pre-pandemic levels. The event, therefore, provides a unique test bed for probing hypotheses about Earth System sensitivities, feedbacks, boundaries and cascades{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR6"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 6}}
\fs20 \super ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR9"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 9}},{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR10"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 10}},{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR11"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 11}}
\fs24 \nosupersub , presuming that the observing systems are in place to capture these responses (Box\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Sec3"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 1}}).\
