\b\fs28 \cf2 Path I: Energy, emissions, climate and air quality\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl280\sa240\partightenfactor0

\b0\fs24 \cf2 Impacts on energy consumption, and associated emissions of greenhouse gases and air pollutants, are likely to cascade across timescales (Fig.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Fig1"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 1}}). In the near-term, reductions in mobility and economic activity have reduced energy use in the commercial, industrial and transportation sectors, and might have increased energy use in the residential sector{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR12"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 12}}
\fs20 \super ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR13"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 13}}
\fs24 \nosupersub . These direct impacts will interact with secondary influences from energy markets, such as the severe short-term drop in oil prices in March and April 2020 (ref.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR14"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 14}}). Further, as with past economic recessions{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR15"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 15}}
\fs20 \super ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR16"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 16}}
\fs24 \nosupersub , energy demands \'97 and the mix of energy sources \'97 are likely to evolve over the course of the economic recovery in response to market forces, public preferences and policy interventions{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR17"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 17}}
\fs20 \super ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR18"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 18}}
\fs24 \nosupersub . This evolution could have long-term effects on the trajectory of decarbonization if, for example, the economic disruption delays the implementation of ambitious climate policy or results in decreased investments in low-carbon energy systems{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR16"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 16}}. Alternatively, large government stimulus spending could target green investments that overhaul outdated infrastructure and accelerate decarbonization{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR18"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 18}}.\
Misunderstandings have arisen with regards to declines in carbon dioxide emissions caused by COVID-19-related disruption, with some interpreting short-term reductions to suggest that austerity of energy consumption could be sufficient to curb the pace of global warming. A reduction in fossil CO
\fs20 \sub 2
\fs24 \nosupersub  emissions proportional to the economic decline{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR15"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 15}} would be dramatic relative to previous declines. For example, the decline in daily CO
\fs20 \sub 2
\fs24 \nosupersub  emissions peaked at >20% in the largest economies during the period of sheltering{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR13"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 13}} (Fig.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Fig2"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2c}}) and the cumulative reduction in global emissions was ~7% from January through April 2020 (ref.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR12"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 12}}) (Fig.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Fig2"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2d}}). However, these daily-scale declines are temporary{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR13"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 13}} and the rebound in emissions that is already evident{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR13"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 13}}
\fs20 \super ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR19"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 19}}
\fs24 \nosupersub  (Fig.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Fig2"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2c}}) supports the likelihood of a reduction in annual emissions that is smaller than 7%.\
Nevertheless, a 5% drop in annual fossil CO
\fs20 \sub 2
\fs24 \nosupersub  emissions from 37 billion metric tonnes per year{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR20"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 20}} would exceed any decline since the end of World War II (ref.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR13"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 13}}). There is a strong basis that such a reduced atmospheric CO
\fs20 \sub 2
\fs24 \nosupersub  growth rate would lead to a reduced ocean carbon sink{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR21"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 21}} and, thus, also a temporary reduction in the rate of ocean acidification. On the other hand, a 5% decrease would still leave annual 2020 emissions at ~35 billion metric tonnes, comparable to emissions in 2013 (ref.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR20"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 20}}). Such a decline \'97 and associated changes in the ocean and land carbon sinks \'97 might not be statistically detectable above the year-to-year variations in the natural carbon cycle and, regardless, global atmospheric CO
\fs20 \sub 2
\fs24 \nosupersub  concentrations will inevitably rise in 2020, continuing a long-term trend. Progress in understanding the carbon-cycle responses to COVID-19 will, therefore, be challenging and, at a minimum, will require new methods for tracking the unprecedented short-term perturbation in emissions through the Earth System.\
Based on past events and fundamental understanding, there are a number of hypotheses of how sheltering-induced changes in atmospheric emissions could influence the climate system more broadly (Fig.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Fig1"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 1}}). On short timescales, reduced air travel decreases the abundance of contrails, which can be detected in the radiation budget (as occurred during the brief cessation of air travel following the 11 September attacks{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR5"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 5}}). The response of atmospheric aerosols to sheltering is likely to vary regionally, with changes in emissions, meteorology and atmospheric chemistry influencing the outcome (Box\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Sec5"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2}}). While reductions in aerosols have occurred in many locations (Fig.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Fig3"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 3}}), they have also been observed to increase in others{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR22"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 22}}, highlighting the important role of secondary chemistry in these assessments. Changes in atmospheric aerosols could further influence cloud and precipitation processes{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR23"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 23}}
\fs20 \super ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR24"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 24}}
\fs24 \nosupersub , and might be detectable in the local surface energy budget{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR25"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 25}}. A reduction in scattering aerosols will also cause warmer surface temperatures over emitting regions{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR26"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 26}} (Fig.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Fig4"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 4}}), potentially manifesting as more frequent and/or intense heatwaves{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR27"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 27}}
\fs20 \super ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR28"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 28}}
\fs24 \nosupersub . If aerosol reductions persist across the Northern Hemisphere, this could have short-term impacts on the onset, intensity and/or intraseasonal variability of monsoon rainfall{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR29"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 29}}
\fs20 \super ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR30"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 30}},{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR31"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 31}}
\fs24 \nosupersub , particularly given that both local and remote aerosol emissions can influence variability within the monsoon season{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR31"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 31}}.\
On longer timescales, changes in the\'a0energy intensity of the economy, the carbon intensity of energy or the pace of deforestation could affect the long-term trajectory of global climate (through the\'a0trajectory of greenhouse gas emissions and associated land and ocean carbon-cycle feedbacks). These effects could go in either direction: for example, in the US electricity sector, coal plants will likely shut down at an accelerated pace as a result of the economic slowdown, continuing a long-term decline{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR32"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 32}}. However, in the transportation sector, policy intervention to stimulate the economy might loosen emissions standards{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR33"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 33}}, increasing emissions relative to the pre-pandemic trajectory.\
The short-term reductions in pollutant emissions have already resulted in noticeable changes in air quality in some regions (Box\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#Sec5"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 2}}). If sustained, improved air quality could yield multiple benefits. These include improved crop health{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR34"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 34}}, as air pollution can reduce regional harvests by as much as 30% (ref.{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR35"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 35}}). In addition, ambient air pollution is a significant cause of premature death and disease worldwide{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR36"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 36}}, even from short-term exposure{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR37"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 37}}
\fs20 \super ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR38"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 38}}
\fs24 \nosupersub . Several well-documented historical examples illustrate how decreased ambient air pollution can improve human health{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR39"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 39}}. These include effects from short-term reductions in traffic, travel and/or industrial activities associated with events such as the 1996 Atlanta Olympic Games{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR40"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 40}} and 2008 Beijing Olympics{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR41"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 41}}
\fs20 \super ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR42"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 42}},{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR43"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 43}},{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR44"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 44}},{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR45"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 45}}
\fs24 \nosupersub . While associations between air quality and health outcomes are hypothesized in studies of the current pandemic{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR46"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 46}}
\fs20 \super ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR47"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 47}}
\fs24 \nosupersub , understanding the role of air quality as an indicator for\'a0the epidemic trajectory is an emerging challenge. Further, any health improvements resulting from improved air quality during the pandemic should not be viewed as a \'91benefit\'92 of the pandemic but, rather, as an accidental side effect of the sheltering that was imposed to protect public health from the virus.\
Some of the most lasting impacts of the COVID-19 crisis on climate and air quality could occur via insights into the calculation of critical policy parameters. Two of the most important, and controversial, are the value of mortality risk reduction (sometimes termed the value of a statistical life, or VSL) and the pure rate of time preference (or PRTP), which is one component of the social discount rate and measures willingness to trade off well-being over time. The VSL is important to the analysis of all environmental regulation in the United States and can determine whether environmental regulations as mundane as a labelling requirement for toxic chemicals will pass a cost\'96benefit test. The PRTP is important in evaluating long-term societal trade-offs \'97 most notably, climate-change regulation \'97 and can be important in calculating an economic value of avoiding climate damages{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR48"}}{\fldrslt 
\fs20 \cf3 \super \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 48}}
\fs20 \super ,{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.nature.com/articles/s43017-020-0079-1#ref-CR49"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 49}}
\fs24 \nosupersub . With a higher PRTP, aggressive mitigation of greenhouse gases becomes less attractive, while a low rate, which places relatively higher value on the well-being of future generations, suggests that far more aggressive regulation of today\'92s emissions is warranted.\
Both the VSL and the PRTP can be difficult to quantify. However, the COVID-19 crisis is making these trade-offs more explicit, as governments, communities and individuals make historic decisions that reflect underlying preferences for current and future consumption and the trade-off between different types of economic activity and individual and collective risk. The diverse responses to the unusual conditions during the pandemic could reveal far more about how different societies manage these trade-offs than has been revealed in the last half-century. As those insights are incorporated into the formal policy-making apparatus, they will have lasting effects on the regulations that impact the long-term trajectory of climate and air quality.\
